# Conventional Commits

All commit messages MUST follow the [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/) specification.

## Format

```
<type>(<scope>): <description>

[optional body]

[optional footer]
```

## Types

| Type | When to use |
|------|-------------|
| `feat` | New feature or behavior |
| `fix` | Bug fix |
| `refactor` | Code change that neither fixes a bug nor adds a feature |
| `style` | Formatting, missing semicolons, etc. (no logic change) |
| `test` | Adding or updating tests |
| `docs` | Documentation only changes |
| `chore` | Build process, dependency updates, tooling |
| `perf` | Performance improvements |
| `ci` | CI/CD configuration changes |
| `revert` | Reverts a previous commit |

## Rules

- Type and description are **mandatory**.
- Scope is optional but recommended for clarity (e.g., `feat(auth): ...`).
- Description must be lowercase and imperative mood: `add`, `fix`, `update` — not `added`, `fixes`, `updating`.
- No period at the end of the description.
- Breaking changes must include `BREAKING CHANGE:` in the footer or a `!` after the type: `feat!: rename login endpoint`.

## Examples

```
feat(packages): add pickup creation flow
fix(auth): handle expired token refresh
refactor(cubit): simplify state emission logic
docs: add README for create_pickup feature
chore: update flutter dependencies
```

## Anti-patterns

```
# ❌ BAD
git commit -m "fix bug"
git commit -m "WIP"
git commit -m "changes"
git commit -m "Fixed the login issue."

# ✅ GOOD
git commit -m "fix(auth): resolve null pointer on login response"
git commit -m "feat(packages): add package listing screen"
```
